INTRODUCTION

Below is the description of the dataset

  • cust_ID: Customer ID
  • region: Region of the customer
  • tenure: Number of months the customer has been with the company
  • age: Age of the customer
  • marital: Marital status
  • address: Number of years the customer has lived at their current address
  • income: Income of the customer
  • ed: Level of education
  • employ: Number of years the customer has been employed
  • retire: Whether the customer is retired
  • gender: Gender of the customer
  • reside: Number of people living in the household
  • tollfree, equip, callcard, wireless: Different service subscriptions
  • longmon, tollmon, equipmon, cardmon, wiremon: Monthly spending on various services
  • churn: Churn status of whether the customer has left the service

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Adjusting for the encoded churn column name
X = CutomerChurnData.drop(['churn_Y'], axis=1)
y = CutomerChurnData['churn_Y']

# Splitting the dataset into training (0.7) and testing (0.3) sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
In [125]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
model_DT = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion="entropy", random_state=1, max_depth=3)
model_DT.fit(X_train, y_train)
predictions = model_DT.predict(X_test)

Key Findings:

"Tenure" is a strong predictor of customer behavior, indicating the importance of rewarding loyal customers.

Other significant factors include 'equipmon', 'callwait', and 'internet_Y', highlighting areas to focus on for reducing churn.

Conclusion:

Our decision tree model achieved an 82% accuracy rate in predicting customer attrition after thorough preprocessing.

Evaluation metrics provided detailed insights into model performance, guiding actionable interventions to address turnover drivers.

Discussion:

While effective in identifying non-churned customers, the model showed limitations in predicting churn accurately.

Actionable strategies, such as improving customer service and optimizing loyalty programs, can be derived from the analysis of key drivers.

Limitations:

Further exploration of advanced algorithms and techniques may enhance predictive accuracy and adaptability to evolving consumer behaviors.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
